b
A fracture plane on which σn c acts exclusively is not conceivable because the fracture resistance of the action plane against compressive stress is R⊥ Ac=∞ (cp. Visualisation of the IFF criterion section).

Puck’s theory meets FEA on the level of the material description. Thus, it is introduced within the subroutine for user-defined material behaviour UMAT.6 Its task is to provide


the particular state of stress for an input state of strain;

the relevant parameters of Puck’s failure theory;

the Jacobian matrix δΔσ/δΔɛ for all stress/strain components.

When confined into a laminate, the lamina’s IFF strengths are observed to be higher than measured in isolated UD laminae.27 The lay-up configuration apparently obstructs the development of Modes A and B cracks (cp. ‘Considerations on different IFF fracture modes’ section). While the effect itself is undisputable, there is only little information on its quantity. Therefore, in all the laminate Test Cases (Cases 8–12), the measured basic strengths are multiplied with the following roughly estimated factors:


in-plane transverse tensile strength R⊥2 t: 1.35;

in-plane transverse/longitudinal shear strength R⊥‖21: 1.175.
